I"Å<p>When Greg Daues at the <a href="https://resources.istcoalition.org/national-center-for-supercomputing-applications" target="_blank">National Center for Supercomputing Applications (NCSA)</a> needed to transfer 460 Terabytes of NCSA files from <a href="https://in2p3.cnrs.fr/en/node/11" target="_blank">the National Institute of Nuclear and Particle Physics (IN2P3)</a> in Lyon, France to Urbana, Illinois, for a project they were working with <a href="https://www.fnal.gov/" target="_blank">FNAL</a>, <a href="https://cc.in2p3.fr/en/" target="_blank">CC-IN2P3</a> and the <a href="https://www.lsst.org/" target="_blank">Rubin Data Production team</a>, he turned to the <a href="https://research.cs.wisc.edu/htcondor/" target="_blank">HTCondor High Throughput system</a>, not to run computationally intensive jobs, as many do, but to manage the hundreds of thousands of I/O bound transfers.</p>
